.SH ENCRYPT/DECRYPT

.PP
The \(aqenc\(aq and \(aqdec\(aq commands encrypt and decrypt files using a password. If no output path is specified using \(aq-o\(aq or \(aq-out\(aq then they will create an output file whose name is the name of the input file with either \(aq.enc\(aq or \(aq.dec\(aq appended. They will not overwrite an existing file, even if that filename is suplied with \(aq-out\(aq.
.SH REVOKING CERTIFICATES

.PP
Certificate revocation is a two-step process. You first revoke the certificate by registering it as revoked against it\(aqs Certificate Authority. This requires specifying the C.A. and supplying the certificate file:
.nf
.ft CW

.RS
.EX

certool.lua revoke /etc/ssl/certs/mycert.crt \-ca myca
.RE
.EE
.fi
.in
.ad b
.nop  
.PP
and The certificate is added to the C.A.\(aqs database of revoked certificates. Next a \(aqcertificate revocation list\(aq is created containing all the revoked certificates in the C.A. database
.nf
.ft CW

.RS
.EX

certtool.lua crl \-ca myca \-o /tmp/myca.crl
.RE
.EE
.fi
.in
.ad b
.nop  
.PP
\(aqmyca.crl\(aq can then be supplied to programs like openvpn and webservers to notify them of certificates that have been revoked.
.SH ZEROSSL

.PP
The zerossl: commands are somewhat experimental. You must supply your API key using either the -api command-line argument, or by setting an environment variable \(aqZEROSSL_API_KEY\(aq. Validation using email has been seen to work, other validation methods are untested
.SH EXAMPLES

.PP
Show certificate details
.nf
.ft CW

.RS
.EX

